solutions.content:
**1st Approach: Two Pointers**
The idea behind the first approach is to to use two pointers starting from 0 and 1 respectively.
1. If the value in the even pointer is even then no need to swap, just increment it by 2.
2. Same applies for the odd value and pointer.
3. If those conditions aren't true, then swap the values to set them in the correct position.

**Complexity Analysis**
Time Complexity: `O(n)` where `n` is the size of the array.
Space Complexity: `O(1)`.
```
vector<int> sortArrayByParityII(vector<int>& nums) {
    int i = 0, j = 1, n = nums.size();
    while(i < n && j < n) {
        if(nums[i] % 2 == 0)
            i += 2;
        else if(nums[j] % 2 != 0)
            j += 2;
        else {
            swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
            i += 2;
            j += 2;
        }
    }
    return nums;
}
```

**2nd Approach: Partitioning and Sorting**
This key of this approach is to split the array into two sorted parts. The preprocessed array should look like the following <kbd>a = {e<sub>1</sub>, e<sub>2</sub>, ..., e<sub>n/2</sub>, o<sub>1</sub>, o<sub>2</sub>, ..., o<sub>n/2</sub>}</kbd>.
1. Partition the array with even numbers.
2. Sort the array in-place based on the partitioning iterator.
3. Now, the array is split into even then odd numbers respectively.
4. Only swap the values to their corresponding position.

**Complexity Analysis**
Time Complexity: `O(n)` where `n` is the size of the array.
Space Complexity: `O(1)`.

```
void sortByParity(vector<int>& nums) {
    auto itr = partition(nums.begin(), nums.end(), [](const int val) {
        return val % 2 == 0;
    });
    sort(itr, nums.end());
}

vector<int> sortArrayByParityII_2(vector<int>& nums) {
    sortByParity(nums);
    int i = 1, j = nums.size() / 2;
    while(i < j && j < nums.size()) {
        swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
        i += 2;
        ++j;
    }
    return nums;
}
```

